Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Quantum Noisy Dynamics", "TechNoteSection",
 CellTags->"Section14",
 CellID->55650219,ExpressionUUID->"9b0274c6-455d-4497-96e7-0b8b0ad6dbb5"],

Cell["\<\
When a system interacts with its environment, the dynamics of the system can \
no longer be described by the Schr\[ODoubleDot]dinger equation. More \
importantly, it is not unitary.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1157844288,ExpressionUUID->"48cbb40b-135c-4e02-a686-e735632f1666"],

Cell["\<\
It may not be surprising at first glance since similar effects also occur in \
classical mechanics. For example, a ball thrown up in the air interacts with \
various molecules and small particles in the air, and it does not follow \
Newton\[CloseCurlyQuote]s equation of motion. The dynamics become dissipative \
as is described by additional damping terms in the equation of motion. In \
effect, damping terms arise because we are ignoring the small molecules and \
particles that disturb the ball.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->682199169,ExpressionUUID->"8b36c328-b696-4013-9d4b-12fbed0959b5"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "However, ignoring the environmental degrees of freedom in quantum theory \
brings about far more profound effects. It causes not only the dissipation of \
energy of the system to the environment, but also the effect of so-called ",
 StyleBox["quantum decoherence",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", the loss of ",
 StyleBox["quantumness",
  IgnoreSpellCheck->True],
 " (Zurek, 1991, 2002). Here, we outline the basic formalism for decoherence, \
but further details will be discussed in ",
 ButtonBox["quantum noise and decoherence",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/QuantumNoiseAndDecoherence"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1231272054,ExpressionUUID->"82d68af6-1f46-4263-96f1-b52fddfeb2e6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Suppose that the system is initially in a state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    TemplateBox[{"\[Psi]"},
     "Ket"], "\[Element]", "\[ScriptCapitalH]"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"78d5aca4-e297-436c-bec6-95deff773fca"],
 " and the environment is in ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    TemplateBox[{"\[Epsilon]"},
     "Ket"], "\[Element]", "\[ScriptCapitalE]"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"6be7fb00-2270-4a38-ad6d-7b2547486a7a"],
 ". Thus, the initial state of the total system is"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1539622949,ExpressionUUID->"b2645678-69ed-4d99-ad73-f7040c376e79"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    TemplateBox[{
      RowBox[{"\[CapitalPsi]", "(", "0", ")"}]},
     "Ket"], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      TemplateBox[{"\[Psi]"},
       "Ket"], "\[CircleTimes]", 
      TemplateBox[{"\[Epsilon]"},
       "Ket"]}], "\[Element]", 
     RowBox[{"\[ScriptCapitalH]", "\[CircleTimes]", "\[ScriptCapitalE]"}]}]}],
    TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a39ff7d8-cebc-4cd7-9548-860d5fe8c813"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1412441140,ExpressionUUID->"3e646daf-513b-4509-b1cb-8ce77c18e526"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Then, let the system and the environment interact with each other. As a \
closed system, the evolution of the total system is governed by a unitary \
time-evolution operator ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["U", "tot"], "(", "t", ")"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"6b2b265a-e8e9-4ac0-9a37-42e04a777c26"],
 ","
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->614006042,ExpressionUUID->"1813ee30-ccf7-4c9c-8339-d21b052481d9"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    TemplateBox[{
      RowBox[{"\[CapitalPsi]", "(", "t", ")"}]},
     "Ket"], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["U", "tot"], "(", "t", ")"}], 
     RowBox[{
      TemplateBox[{"\[Psi]"},
       "Ket"], "\[CircleTimes]", 
      TemplateBox[{"\[Epsilon]"},
       "Ket"]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "23b53b82-2ad7-4ae6-ba7b-c9a1ed7a0c41"],
 ","
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->940624059,ExpressionUUID->"1102cb1a-02f9-4dae-8ddf-50f5d08d6e14"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "in accordance with ",
 ButtonBox["Postulate 2",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/TimeEvolution"],
 ". The system- environment coupling tends to build entanglement, so the \
state |\[CapitalPsi](t)\:27e9 cannot be factorized in general. Without \
comprehensive knowledge of the environment, the state of the system alone is \
thus a mixed state (see ",
 ButtonBox["Quantum States",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/QuantumStates"],
 ")."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1441434046,ExpressionUUID->"64d011b2-7796-4884-a8d6-476dffa333e9"],

Cell["\<\
Specifically, one can get the density matrix representing the mixed state by \
tracing out the information of the environment from the total state |\
\[CapitalPsi](t)\:27e9,\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->418989315,ExpressionUUID->"08c02205-8c28-4ba3-983f-a3998f246605"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\t",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"\[Rho]", "(", "t", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["Tr", "\[ScriptCapitalE]"], 
      TemplateBox[{
        RowBox[{"\[CapitalPsi]", "(", "t", ")"}]},
       "Ket"], 
      TemplateBox[{
        RowBox[{"\[CapitalPsi]", "(", "t", ")"}]},
       "Bra"]}], "=", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["Tr", "\[ScriptCapitalE]"], 
      RowBox[{
       SubscriptBox["U", "tot"], "(", "t", ")"}], 
      RowBox[{"(", 
       RowBox[{
        TemplateBox[{"\[Psi]"},
         "Ket"], 
        RowBox[{
         TemplateBox[{"\[Psi]"},
          "Bra"], "\[CircleTimes]", 
         TemplateBox[{"\[Epsilon]"},
          "Ket"]}], 
        TemplateBox[{"\[Epsilon]"},
         "Bra"]}], ")"}], 
      RowBox[{
       SubsuperscriptBox["U", "tot", "\[Dagger]"], "(", "t", ")"}]}]}]}], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"81125bae-729e-46a0-99c2-756b0d5ad4fa"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->354538692,ExpressionUUID->"e1e299b8-9877-4e0d-a345-c473cd13d975"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A partial trace over the environment physically corresponds to ignoring the \
degrees of freedom of the environment. In general, the dynamics of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[Rho]", 
    RowBox[{"(", "t", ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "21cad05f-fbf4-4e3b-a9f8-0d190878c386"],
 " is thus very complicated. However, there are two essential points: First, \
the dynamics is no longer unitary. Second, through entanglement with the \
environment, the quantum state of the system loses coherence."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1612159666,ExpressionUUID->"b519ec4b-dbc2-4cb2-b43c-9d6ff5b2dc6a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The non-unitary dynamics of a system coupled to the environment can be most \
efficiently described via the quantum operation formalism. See ",
 ButtonBox["Quantum Noise and Decoherence",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/tutorial/QuantumNoiseAndDecoherence"],
 " for more details."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->766332263,ExpressionUUID->"2368594b-f9a4-46df-a8df-972a25420238"]
}, Open  ]],

